[4] Rabies, bats, human exposure- Indiana
Date: 27 Mar 2012
Source: NECN.com [edited]
http://www.necn.com/03/27/12/Ind-U-student-bitten-by-rabid-bat-in-dor/landing_health.html?&apID=4a20c3e182c64fcc9f340e5de2a363b1

Indiana University student bitten by rabid bat in dorm room
---------------------------------------------
An Indiana University student bitten by a rabid bat while he slept in his Bloomington dorm room is receiving rabies shots.

The Herald-Times reports his roommate and a pest control worker who transported the bat also are receiving the 14-day regimen of shots.

IU spokesman Mark Land says the student was bitten on a hand and shook the bat off in a hallway. The bat was later found alive in the hallway by a residence hall employee who called the pest control worker, who collected the bat and sent it to the Indiana State Department of Health for testing.

Health department spokesman Ken Severson says 2 other bats also tested positive for rabies last week. They were in the Fort Wayne area. Rabies can be fatal if untreated.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Each one of these snippets should serve as a reminder to us that this fatal disease is still very active and requires our vigilance. Protection of us and our pets is important and one of the best ways to build that protective barrier is to have your pets, large and small, vaccinated against rabies.

Dogs, cats, ferrets, horses, show animals such as calves, sheep, and goats should be vaccinated against rabies.

North Carolina may be found on the interactive HealthMap at: http://healthmap.org/r/1s-V
Maryland may be found on the interactive HealthMap at: http://healthmap.org/r/1DmA
Pennsylvania may be found on the interactive HealthMap at: http://healthmap.org/r/1Fgp
Indiana May be found on the interactive HealthMap at: http://healthmap.org/r/1DmR
